social_posts.post_text: Outstretched needles catching those final rays of evening light.
Grateful for the time I get to spend in this place.

Skyline of the Navajo Nation.

I drive past this view frequently and always stare at it in awe. I finally made a stop to take a photo of it on my last pass through.

Zion adventures from this past year that slipped through the cracks. 

We definitely need more canyon time when you guys get back this summer!
Further proof of why Bryce is my favorite national park in the winter.

It's amazing to recognize these patterns preserved in solid rock throughout so many places in the southwest.

Now I'm seeing the process occur firsthand. Geology is pretty rad!

Went back to revisit an old favorite with a new friend!

My goal was to entice her into the peakbagging cult and I'm pretty confident I succeeded with this view.

I've seen this mountain from every angle and it gets me every time. It was fun to see her experience it for the first time with just as much enthusiasm!

More peaks and more adventures on the way, @ccc__christina!

1 lake, 3 different views.

It took me a while to finally make it out to see this one, but luckily there was a peak nearby I wanted to get, which took me right next to it. 

It ended up being great timing because the weather wasn't exactly favorable, so it wasn't crowded! Yay!
Going back into the desert soon (not sure if I've ever really left) for more of these volcanic towers this coming week!

A peakbagging haven in terms of viewpoints. 

These towers were so cool to look at, but the majority of the terrain was heinously crumbly and made scrambling a real challenge. It's no wonder there are no registered ascents on many of these. 

Still a stunning area that I'm happy to have visited. It might even be worth a couple more days of exploring! Hopefully on better rock.
A peakbagging mecca if only the rock quality would support it. Still one of the most impressive groupings of rock towers I've seen in the desert.

"So how do we get up it?"

The perspective in the photo makes it look like such a little thing, but in reality, it's a 300-ft tall butte with sheer cliffs on all sides...except for one. 

We examined three different options at first, none of which were viable due to vertical, loose walls. 

It had juuuuust enough of a weakness on its east face to allow for a semi-exposed 4th class route.

Little by little, each section went up a bit further, eventually leading us to its summit. 

I poorly documented this one since I elected to leave my pack and cameras at the base so they wouldn't impede my climbing. 

All in all, probably the best scrambling and route finding we had during all five days of the trip.

It's not just organ pipe in Organ Pipe Cactus National Monument.

A shot of the classic saguaro and desert haze while hiking back from our last summit.

I still haven't gotten tired of taking guests out here for our tours. 

The best part about Canyonlands is the variety between districts within the park. 

The Needles District, pictured here feels the most immersive as you hike between towers and squeeze down into narrow cracks. 

It only sees 20% of the total visitation in Canyonlands so you're likely to have long stretches of trail all to yourself.
A scene straight out of an old western.

Came out to climb Weavers Needle and got distracted by all the wildflowers still blooming along the way. I can't believe it's been over a month and these flowers are still going strong!

1. Desert penstemon 
2. Fairy duster (in focus), globe mallow
3. Saguaro and brittle brush
4. Purple nightshade
5. Rock daisy (?)
6. Purple verbena
7. Brittle brush
8. Catmint (?)
9. Eastern collared lizard
10. Brittle brush
Scenes from around Joshua Tree National Park this past winter.

We take the best lunch breaks 🙌

This was from an awesome weekend of guide training and knowledge sharing in the Moab area this past April. 

Next up, I fly to Bozeman then off to Yellowstone for another one this weekend. I'm very excited to be back in that park to learn everything I can about it (and hopefully take some great shots in the process).

I've driven past this location countless times and I finally did so with a drone in the back of the car and optimal lighting.

This is one of several anticlinal folds in the geologic strata of the southwest. Think of what would happen if you placed a sheet of paper on a table and pushed both ends toward each other. 

Your compressional force would create an arch in the paper just like we see in the strata here today. Instead of your hands driving compression, it's colliding continents instead.

Add in several million years of precipitation atop that arch. Now you've created several different erosion channels running downward creating these V-shaped patterns in the multicolored rock layers. 

Tectonic geology really is the driver for some of the coolest landscapes. I love that we have so many of them visible in the SW!
It's not a day at Yellowstone without a stop at Grand Prismatic.

An excellent canyon for my first descent into the white domed landscape of Capitol Reef. 

We sure timed this one well. It began to thunder as we navigated through the lower stretch of the canyon beyond the highest rappel. 

Thunder is not something I ever want to hear in a place like this. It definitely adds some fear into the mix. 

Luckily, we were through the narrowest part of the canyon and starting our walk back to the cars when the sky really opened up. 

A really excellent day of canyoneering nonetheless.

Sunset from the Chiricahuas. 

Quite the view as I camped in my Jeep the night before hiking to the summit of Chiricahua Peak.

The last on my list of Arizona Ultras.

Something that's become quite normal for those of us living in not only the western US but also Canada.

Wildfire smoke.

This was taken this past week in southeastern British Columbia as wildfires burn all over the province. 

I stayed with someone who has lived in the area for several years and this has become a normal part of their summer every year. 

Even in planning this trip, we were informed to not wait too far into the season to visit. Otherwise, we'd risk this scenario or having our trip canceled all together.

Despite thoughtful planning, we still encountered these fires. 

People were mostly outside going about their business as usual. There were even a few paddleboarders on the water with their dogs skimming across the glassy lake as the air nearly obscured the mountains a few miles away. 

Obviously, we have no choice but to accept the current situation. It's just sad that it's becoming "the new normal" everyone keeps talking about as our climate begins to tilt askew.

Excellent scramble with excellent views. I didn't want to come down from here. 🇨🇦

I decided to hang around the canyon after the day's tour had ended hoping that the storms would produce some interesting scenes. 

After driving along the rim and sitting in the car for 20 minutes while a storm dumped heavy rain, the skies opened up as expected. 

Seeing the canyon during monsoon season is always worth the time spent dodging the rain.

The Grand Canyons little cousin. 

After I had captured an impressive storm on the south rim earlier that evening, I decided to make another stop at a location I haven't visited in probably 7  years. 

I forgot how impressive it is in its own right.

It was mostly clear when I began my walk, but the rain and thunder came back soon after I had reached the rim. 

Honestly, this was exactly what I was hoping for despite having to snag shots in between hiding my camera in my jacket for protection. 

I got soaked from the waist down...but that was okay. 

I stayed out a bit too long and nearly got locked in here as well. 

I heard several calls back and forth between two Navajo art sellers who had a stand near the highway/parking area. 

I rushed back to the van to see them waiting for me at the gate, ready to lock up for the night.

A smile and a wave as I drove through and they locked up behind me.

I'm very grateful for what they have done to preserve this area and allow people like me to see it. It's truly special.

I really can't complain about all the driving I do when this is one of my travel days between parks.

If only I could manage to make one of these drives without an additional hour of photo stops.

Indigenous peoples history around Bryce Canyon goes back at least 10,000 years beginning with the Ancestral Puebloans, the Fremont and the Southern Paiute; well before mormon settlers moved into the area in the 1850's.

Paiute lore reveals the belief that the enigmatic red rock hoodoos that distinguish Bryce Canyon were “Evil Legend People” (To-when-an-ung-wa) who were turned to stone by the all-powerful Coyote spirit.  The Paiute called these mysterious rock formations Anka-ku-was-a-wits, meaning the “red painted faces.”

Indian Dick, a Paiute elder living on the Kaibab Reservation, told the Bryce Canyon hoodoo legend to a park ranger in 1936:

“Before there were any Indians, the Legend People, To-when-an-ung-wa, lived in that place. There were many of them. They were of many kinds–birds, animals, lizards, and such things, but they looked like people. They were not people. They had power to make themselves look that way. For some reason the Legend People in that place were bad; they did something that was not good, perhaps a fight, perhaps some stole something…the tale is not clear at this point. Because they were bad, Coyote turned them all into rocks. You can see them in that place now all turned into rocks; some standing in rows, some sitting down, some holding onto others. You can see their faces, with paint on them just as they were before they became rocks. The name of that place is Angka-ku-wass-a-wits (red painted faces). This is the story the people tell.”

In this photo taken from Bryce Point, you can begin to understand the perspective of the Pauite and imagine a crowd of people standing together before immediately being turned to stone.
No better place to spend monsoon season than the top of a cinder cone.

It may have been hotter than normal, but at least I got a great view of Rainer without her usual cover.

I thought I was escaping the heat of Phoenix, but got 92° in Seattle when I arrived instead.

Not as bad up here at least. The soak in the lake afterward definitely helped.

Okay the coast is pretty magical as well. 

I didn't quite catch the lowest tide that would have exposed the cool tilted rock formations I was after, but this hazy coastal glow during sunset still delivered some beautiful scenes. 

So different from my first visit back in January of 2017. I'm lucky to have seen this place a second time!
Guiding days at work now sometimes involve hot air balloon rides.

I didn't intend to get a shot of this iconic location while I was in the park, but when it's 30 seconds off the road in perfect lighting, it's 30 seconds off the road. 

Naturally, I had to shoot around the beauty influencer posted up in the best spot while she made her BF take shot after shot after shot. 

I guess they're out at 7:00am too.

Wrapping up the year with my list of favorite peaks from the 2023! Better late than never. 

These all made the list for several reasons. Some had incredible views, some had fun/engaging ascent routes, and others have a fond memory tied to them because of the person/people I got to share it with.

It was a difficult list to narrow down given this years number of summits. My goal was to outdo my total for last year, and I beat that total by an extra 24. 192 summits for the year!

In unranked order:

1: Weavers Needle, AZ
2: Tolmie Peak, WA (with a view of Rainier)
3: Gimli Peak, BC, Canada
4: Peak 2340, AZ
5: Ferns Nipple, UT (pointy thing in the upper right)
6: Peak 1280, CA (view from the summit)
7: Needles Eye, AZ
8: Lucifer Peak, BC, Canada 
9: Bridge Mountain, NV (photo of the bridge off the ascent)
10: Pico De Orizaba, Mexico
Right place at the right time.
Weavers Needle being the ever-present watchtower over the Supes.
